<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>

<activity xml:id="act-nuevoAlgoritmoDeResta" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"> 

<title>Un nuevo algoritmo de resta</title>

<statement>
  <p>Andre y Clare encontraron el valor de <m>528-271</m>. Así empezaron su trabajo.</p>
  <sbsgroup widths="50% 50%">
    <sidebyside>
      <p>Algoritmo de Andre</p>
      <p>Algoritmo de Clare</p>
    </sidebyside>
    <sidebyside>
      <image source="svg-source/tikz-file-147406">
        <shortdescription>resta de 528 y 271 en forma extendida</shortdescription>
      </image>
      <image source="svg-source/tikz-file-147407">
        <shortdescription>resta de 528 y 271 por valor posicional</shortdescription>
      </image>
    </sidebyside>
  </sbsgroup>
  <ol>
    <li><p>Completa los dos algoritmos para encontrar la diferencia.</p></li>
    <li><p>Andre y Clare empezaron a restar de formas distintas. ¿Cómo influyó cada forma de empezar en los pasos que siguieron para encontrar la diferencia?</p></li>
  </ol>
</statement>

<solution>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <ol>
      <li><m>200 + 50 + 7</m> and 257</li>
      <li><p>Sample responses:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>For Andre’s way of getting started, I had to write part of the expanded form for each step. For Clare’s way of getting started, I only recorded one digit for each place value.</li>
          <li>For Andre’s way of getting started, I had to add up the parts of the number at the end, but for Clare’s way, the number was already made from the digits.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </solution>


<!-- ============================================================== 
   Notas profesor <prelude> (se pueden mostrar previo al enunciado)                      
===================================================================  -->
<prelude component="profesor"> 

  <!-- Estándares CCSS asociados -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="ccss-actividad-titulo"/></title> 
    <ul>
      <li> 
        <custom ref="ccss-addressing"/>
        <xref ref="ccss-3-NBT-A-2" text="custom">3.NBT.A.2</xref>
      </li>  
    </ul>
  </paragraphs>

  <!-- Tiempo recomendado -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="recommended-time-titulo"/></title>
    <p>20 minutos</p>
  </paragraphs>

  <!-- Introducción de la actividad -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="narrative-actividad-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <p>The purpose of this activity is for students to learn a subtraction algorithm that records the difference in each place value position as a single digit. The algorithm also records a decomposed hundred as a single digit in the hundreds place and as two digits in the tens place. Students carefully analyze and discuss two different ways to subtract, highlighting similarities and differences and explaining how and why they work (MP6).</p>
  </paragraphs>

  <!-- Launch -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="launch-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Groups of 2</li>
      <li>Display Andre and Clare’s work.</li>
      <li>
        <q>¿En qué se parecen los algoritmos?</q>  (They are both stacked vertically. They show the same two numbers, 528 and 271. They both show a hundred decomposed into 10 tens.)
      </li>
      <li>
        <q>¿En qué son diferentes?</q>  (One pair of numbers is written in expanded form, but the other pair is not. In Andre’s case, the decomposing of a hundred is recorded as 400 and 120. In Clare’s case, it is written as 4 in the hundreds place and 12 in the tens place.)
      </li>
      <li>1 minute: quiet think time</li>
      <li>2 minutes: partner discussion</li>
      <li>Share and record responses. Emphasize the different ways of recording the decompositions.</li>
      <li>
        <q>Observamos que este nuevo algoritmo usa menos dígitos porque no se escribe el valor de cada dígito. Simplemente registramos hasta 2 dígitos en cada posición para saber cuántas centenas, decenas o unidades hay</q>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </paragraphs>


  <!-- Instrucciones para el desarrollo de la actividad -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="instructions-teacher-actividad-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <q>Tómense unos minutos en silencio para trabajar en la actividad. Después, discutan sus respuestas con su pareja</q>
      </li>
      <li>3–5 minutes: independent work time</li>
      <li>2–3 minutes: partner discussion</li>
    </ul>
  </paragraphs>

</prelude>


<!-- ============================================================== 
   Notas profesor <postlude> (se pueden mostrar después del enunciado)                      
===================================================================  -->
<postlude component="profesor">

  <!-- Síntesis de la actividad -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="synthesis-actividad-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Invite students to share their work for completing each algorithm.</li>
      <li>
        <q>¿Qué hicieron de una forma diferente al completar cada uno de estos problemas?</q>  (With Andre’s work I subtracted all the place values, then I had to add up all the parts of the difference. With Clare’s work once I subtracted the digits in each place value, the answer was complete.)
      </li>
    </ul>
  </paragraphs>

</postlude>

</activity>